 <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Boosey  .","Americanized form of German   Busse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessey","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): perhaps a variant of   Bussey  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Côte-d'Or and Loire named Bessey, from the Gallo-Roman estate <i>Bassiacum</i>, from the Roman personal name <i>Bassius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."]},{"name":"Boosey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>bosy</i> ‘ox-stall, cow-stall’ (Old English <i>bōsig</i>)."]},{"name":"Bussie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bussey  , of Norman origin. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bucey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bussey  ."]},{"name":"Busey","meanings":["English: variant of   Bussey  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Lambert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."],"variants":[{"name":"Lammert","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]},{"name":"Lamprecht","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lambert Bussey was born in 1225, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Hugh Bussey, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Dive, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Dive. He died in 1293, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1225–1293":"1225–1293","1225–1317":"1225–1317","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1306":"1306","1317":"1317","Hougham, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1225–1293":"1225–1293","1225–1317":"1225–1317","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1306":"1306","1317":"1317","Hougham, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1225–1293":"1225–1293","1225–1317":"1225–1317","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1306":"1306","1317":"1317","Hougham, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lambert Bussey est né en 1225, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Sir Hugh Bussey, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth Dive, avait 22 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Elizabeth Dive. Il 